    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26b.63"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">63</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">ARTHUR SULLIVANT HOFFMAN
                        <lb/>
                    CARMEL, NEW YORK</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>Sept. 26, 1958</dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear Dr Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Thanks to Austin Phelps, here are you and he out of the past and it's good to meet you both again.</p>
                
                <p>You take me back a few years beyond Adventure to Watson's Magazine and its unique career up over a shoe store on 42nd Street and me as its editor's entire staff - I even ran an extensive woman's department as Mrs Louise <hi rend="caps">H.</hi> Miller. Its managing editor - Tom Watson the editor; mostly, thank God, from his home in the South.</p>
                
                <p>Do you by any chance remember Charles Fort, a prose contributor and a unique one. Years later I found a bunch of literati or philosophers had built up a cul<del>y</del><add>t</add> of some kind abou<del>r</del><add>t</add> him or someone of the same name. "My" Charles Fort washed dishes for restaurants until he had money <del>r</del><add>e</add>nough to feed him for another round at writing, then more dishes. Fiction and sketches of his near-slum neighbors, very vivid and alive. Took me out one night and introduced me to a wonderful collection of filibusters, saloon keepers, prize fighters and their lady friends.</p>
                
                <p>It's long years since those days but vivid things come back from them. At eighty-two I still hope for time to put the more amusing ones on paper, perhaps none of them are so amusing as the hope.</p>
                
                <p>Who's Who shows me what a full life you've had. My congratulations and my good wishes.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Sincerely</salute>
                
                    <signed>Arthur S. Hoffman</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
